If you declare a global array in a shader and access it via a pixel shader it will always return 0 regardless of the actual value stored.

If anyone knows any workarounds please let me know. Here is an example of the issue.

    float test = 1;
    float test2[2] = { 0.5, 1 };
    float4 PixelShaderFunction(float4 position : SV_Position, float4 c : COLOR0, float2 uv : TEXCOORD0) : COLOR
    {
    	return float4(test, 0, 0, 1); //This returns red (1,0,0,1)
    	return float4(test2[0], 0, 0, 1); //This returns black (0,0,0,1) , I would expect dark red
    	return float4(test2[1], 0, 0, 1); //This returns black (0,0,0,1) , I would expect red
    }

It is a major pain when converting shaders to monogame.

I have tried changing the shader flags, and have tried using the uniform keyword.

I have tested this in both 3.5 and the current development branch

I am using MonoGame 3.6.0.906 on MacOS. I am trying to get some mouse input code working, but I have found some strange behaviour. It appears that the mouse position does not update when the left button is pressed. This makes it impossible to implement mouse dragging input.

To investigate, I added print statements when the left mouse button is pressed, when is released and the mouse position every update. I then tried clicking and dragging. The mouse definitely moved when the left button was down.

Here is the log:

```
...
{X:89 Y:384}
{X:89 Y:385}
{X:90 Y:386}
pressed
released
{X:91 Y:386}
{X:94 Y:386}
{X:96 Y:386}
...
```
As can be seen, the mouse position does not change when the left button is down. 

Here is the code: 

```
    MouseState previousMouseState;

    protected override void Update(GameTime gameTime)
    {
        var mouseState = Mouse.GetState();

        if (mouseState.LeftButton == ButtonState.Pressed && 
            previousMouseState.LeftButton == ButtonState.Released)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("pressed");
        }

        if (mouseState.LeftButton == ButtonState.Released && 
            previousMouseState.LeftButton == ButtonState.Pressed)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("released");
        }

        if (mouseState.Position != previousMouseState.Position)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(mouseState.Position);
        }

        previousMouseState = mouseState;

        base.Update(gameTime);
    }
```

SO question: [http://stackoverflow.com/questions/40562644/why-does-my-mouse-position-not-update-when-the-left-button-is-pressed](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/40562644/why-does-my-mouse-position-not-update-when-the-left-button-is-pressed)

This is a bit inconsistent, because I have 2 identical classes and its only occurring on one. This only occurs during Deserialization. 

On line 284 of the monogame IntermediateSerializer class. Type foundType is assigned via LINQ using reflection. 

foundType = (from assembly in AppDomain.CurrentDomain.GetAssemblies()
                         from type in assembly.GetTypes()
                         where type.FullName == typeName || type.Name == typeName
                         select type).FirstOrDefault();

var test1 = (from assembly in AppDomain.CurrentDomain.GetAssemblies()
                        from type in assembly.GetTypes()
                        where type.FullName == typeName
                        select type);

var test2 = (from assembly in AppDomain.CurrentDomain.GetAssemblies()
                         from type in assembly.GetTypes()
                         where type.Name == typeName
                         select type); 

Class1 the results view count == 1, So using FirstOrDefault() for the query is fine.
test1:   [0] {Name = "Class1" FullName = "Class1"}
test2:   [0] {Name = "Class1" FullName = "Class1"}


Class2 the results view count == 2, using FirstOrDefault() for the query is giving me bad info and causing deserialization to fail.
test1:   [0] {Name = "Class1" FullName = "Class1"}

test2:   [0] {Name = "Class1" FullName = "System.Xml.Schema.FacetsChecker+FacestsCompiler+Class1"}
test2:   [1] {Name = "Class1" FullName = "Class1"}

Exception.Message: "Type 'System.Xml.Schema.FacetsChecker+FacetsCompiler+Map' is not assignable to 'Map'."


I was not using namespaces on class1 and class2 when this occurred, however when I use namespaces an incorrect namespace is generated. Ex. my namespace is TiledEditor.Objects.Map and it generated a type.Name of "Map.Map".

I have temporarily resolved this for my situation, but the underlying issue persists.

The fix in my situation was to remove the namespaces on my classes that are serialized and change the query to use AND instead of OR:

foundType = (from assembly in AppDomain.CurrentDomain.GetAssemblies()
                         from type in assembly.GetTypes()
                         where type.FullName == typeName && type.Name == typeName
                         select type).FirstOrDefault();

I am not sure why this is happening, but it is very inconsistent. Anyone have any ideas why this is occurring?
